pageTitle: Solitaires stay around and stake out territories all winter | CanyonCourier.com
TableContextTimeStampAfterTable: {20466=The first Townsend’s solitaire that I ever saw was shortly after we moved to Colorado in April 1965. I was looking around our new yard and saw a strange gray bird just across the road, clinging to a giant mullein stalk in the open valley above Little Cub Creek. I watched it digging insects out of the dead mullein stalk and thought how often I had seen downy woodpeckers acting in the same manner., 33290=Copyright © 2015, 25971=Canyon Courier | circulation@canyoncourier.com | 303-350-1030 27902 Meadow Drive, Ste 200, Evergreen, CO 80439 Office Hours are 8:00 a.m. to 5:00 p.m., Monday through Friday}
